1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:25,920
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:26,373 --> 00:00:33,901
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:33,920 --> 00:00:47,094
So, just roving around the topic of meditation, daily life, practice and all that.

4
00:00:47,113 --> 00:00:51,918
I suppose one interesting question we might ask is one of these if questions.

5
00:00:53,981 --> 00:00:54,962
But,

6
00:00:56,308 --> 00:01:06,343
Why didn't the Buddha return to lay life once he'd become fully Self-realized?

7
00:01:11,569 --> 00:01:16,757
Good question, isn't it?

8
00:01:17,778 --> 00:01:20,662
Well, I think practically he'd ...

9
00:01:21,587 --> 00:01:47,004
become used to the wandering life and the first people remember that he taught was his old companions who were also wandering ascetics and they very quickly became sort of members of his order you know very shortly after that very quickly people wanted to follow him become his disciples

10
00:01:47,811 --> 00:01:51,876
And the first ordination, as it's called, was a simple word, ehi, come.

11
00:01:53,179 --> 00:02:02,432
So when somebody said, well, I'd like to, you know, follow your teachings, be with you, join your sangha, your community, you just said, ehi, come along.

12
00:02:04,073 --> 00:02:13,026
When the sangha was established, then the second type of ordination was established, where people took refuge in the Buddha, the Dharma, and the sangha.

13
00:02:13,832 --> 00:02:24,474
which has now become the layway of determining your commitment to the Dharma.

14
00:02:24,495 --> 00:02:28,544
And then by around about, I suppose, well, they say about 20 years.

15
00:02:28,584 --> 00:02:31,149
For 20 years, the people who joined were of high caliber.

16
00:02:31,849 --> 00:02:34,997
Then it began to slide down the slippery slope.

17
00:02:35,602 --> 00:02:45,573
And the ordination then became quite a long one, maybe half an hour or so, in which certain questions had to be asked, such as, are you still in government employ?

18
00:02:46,555 --> 00:02:47,335
Are you in debt?

19
00:02:48,417 --> 00:02:49,097
Are you a man?

20
00:02:49,717 --> 00:02:51,920
It was a very interesting one.

21
00:02:51,941 --> 00:02:52,762
Are you a human being?

22
00:02:54,723 --> 00:02:58,627
So various sorts of people tried to join the order.

23
00:02:58,647 --> 00:03:04,495
One of the reasons, just as a little side, was that the great court physician

24
00:03:04,913 --> 00:03:08,228
would treat the Buddha's monks free of charge.

25
00:03:10,740 --> 00:03:14,417
And of course, occasionally people would join the order in order to be...

26
00:03:14,887 --> 00:03:17,691
treated full of charge, treated without charge.

27
00:03:17,911 --> 00:03:22,397
So one of the questions is, are you sick?

28
00:03:22,418 --> 00:03:27,625
And the rule is you can't ordain somebody who has certain illnesses.

29
00:03:29,407 --> 00:03:36,016
I remember a sorry case happened with somebody with AIDS, you see, came with AIDS, wanted to join the order, they weren't ready.

30
00:03:39,439 --> 00:03:48,792
so uh... very quickly he uh... informed this particular grouping early on uh... you know

31
00:03:49,243 --> 00:04:02,180
Very shortly after his realization he did go home and hugged his mother or his stepmother and met all his family, his extended family.

32
00:04:03,461 --> 00:04:11,890
And of course that was the moment when his wife said to their child, Rahula, go and ask your father for your inheritance.

33
00:04:12,412 --> 00:04:16,516
So obviously there there's some feeling that the Buddha's not going to come back to lay life.

34
00:04:16,987 --> 00:04:23,223
and he wants him to make him the heir to his grandfather's fortunes etc.

35
00:04:23,262 --> 00:04:23,644
etc.

36
00:04:24,425 --> 00:04:30,220
but the Buddha of course ordains him that was his inheritance the Dharma

37
00:04:31,177 --> 00:04:35,144
And there are two charming discourses.

38
00:04:35,223 --> 00:04:39,369
The one when he's given when he's about, I don't know, 12 maybe, something like that.

39
00:04:40,190 --> 00:04:44,235
And the Buddha's giving him all sorts of reasons why he shouldn't tell fibs.

40
00:04:45,557 --> 00:04:46,740
It's a lovely little one.

41
00:04:46,759 --> 00:04:52,927
And then later on when he's 18, and he's obviously struggling with perhaps leaving the monastic life.

42
00:04:52,947 --> 00:04:56,392
And eventually he also becomes fully realized.

43
00:05:03,983 --> 00:05:20,708
So, I mean, apart from perhaps that practical reason, it would seem that, generally speaking, once one moves towards end game, really nothing there to draw one back into late life.

44
00:05:22,651 --> 00:05:27,918
And that's just one of those things that happens, I suppose.

45
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:32,826
But on the other hand, there are lay people who become fully self-realized.

46
00:05:33,396 --> 00:05:35,379
One that I remember is a cobbler, you see.

47
00:05:36,482 --> 00:05:37,762
An ordinary old cobbler.

48
00:05:39,545 --> 00:05:40,788
Becomes fully self-realized.

49
00:05:42,269 --> 00:05:49,259
So, why is it, I mean, one question is, why is it that there weren't more people who were self-realized who were lay people?

50
00:05:49,319 --> 00:05:55,509
And I think the reason there is the ambience that you're working in.

51
00:05:55,529 --> 00:05:57,733
The Buddha talks about lay life being dusty.

52
00:05:58,192 --> 00:05:59,235
That's the word he uses.

53
00:06:00,497 --> 00:06:08,447
And if we just look at our society, you can see that most people just aren't on the spiritual wavelength.

54
00:06:08,468 --> 00:06:10,990
So when you work with people like that, there's always a drag.

55
00:06:11,331 --> 00:06:12,473
They're not supporting you.

56
00:06:13,113 --> 00:06:20,442
It's like there's a constant negativity towards what you're trying to do.

57
00:06:22,065 --> 00:06:24,007
I mean, consider being in a, say,

58
00:06:24,848 --> 00:06:51,125
somewhere like Saudi Arabia or one of the virtually all Muslim countries and you yourself want to do the five times a day prayer and all that well you wouldn't be considered silly or stupid right there in the middle of the office they'd all join in probably and that's what we lack in today's society this sort of support from other people in our ordinary lives

59
00:06:54,564 --> 00:07:19,122
And I'm always at pains to say to people that the jewel of the collection, the Satipaṭṭhāna discourse, which is the fullest discourse on how to become liberated, the actual techniques, what we are practicing now, not in its detail but in its general format, was given to the people of

60
00:07:19,237 --> 00:07:46,206
Kamasadamma they were a tribe you could call them I suppose or a clan or whatever called the Kurums and they lived in what now you would recognise as round about Delhi they travelled quite a bit you know he was all over the place on that Gangetic plain and he'd been up there and given them some teachings and when he returned on this occasion he was

61
00:07:46,591 --> 00:08:15,466
taken by the fact that they were actually doing what he suggested and very mindful and there was no well talk the gossip none of that no argumentation all that sort of stuff so he delivered to them this Ekkaya no Mago this one way path leading to liberation which we now call the Vipassana only path to them the lay people he said

62
00:08:16,509 --> 00:08:20,855
not addressed to the monks or anything.

63
00:08:20,875 --> 00:08:28,144
So he himself had no doubt that a lay person could become liberated.

64
00:08:28,384 --> 00:08:29,365
He wouldn't have done that otherwise.

65
00:08:29,586 --> 00:08:40,639
He'd have given some general discussion, which he would normally start with for people who hadn't met him, about good and bad, karma, the gods, living the good life.

66
00:08:40,659 --> 00:08:44,966
And only when he felt that they were ready for it, he'd hit them with the Four Noble Truths.

67
00:08:44,985 --> 00:08:45,927
He didn't start with that.

68
00:08:47,206 --> 00:08:49,948
So here he's got an orderly people.

69
00:08:50,028 --> 00:09:02,485
I mean, we're talking about pre-industrial societies, farmers living communally with a sort of committee, a committee ruling, a pastoral, more of a pastoral society.

70
00:09:03,245 --> 00:09:11,436
Although there was a great movement at that time towards cities, monarchical rule, the politics were changing.

71
00:09:11,655 --> 00:09:16,302
And there was a rise also of the merchant class, which hadn't existed before.

72
00:09:17,817 --> 00:09:24,004
So he lived in times which were changing, not as viciously as ours, but definitely changing.

73
00:09:24,264 --> 00:09:27,106
And it was felt by a lot of people, I think.

74
00:09:27,126 --> 00:09:40,201
That dislocation when you get times of change, and that was one thing that I think fueled the amount of men who went into the forests and lived a solitary life.

75
00:09:40,221 --> 00:09:47,789
There weren't that many women, partly because of the sexism, of course, and partly because of the danger as well.

76
00:09:50,470 --> 00:10:04,846
And so I think there are practical reasons why he didn't want to return, but I think that also there are spiritual reasons that at that level nothing attracts, nothing attracts back into that form.

77
00:10:08,369 --> 00:10:16,258
But he gave very clear pointers as to how we can turn the lay life into a spiritual life.

78
00:10:18,482 --> 00:10:47,629
and in my e-reminders which I think all of you get and read diligently yes thank you I'm going through a day in the life of you know and just sort of delineating how it's possible to turn everything into a spiritual practice so you're doing the same thing you see you're doing the same things you're still getting up you're still dressing you're still brushing your teeth

79
00:10:47,947 --> 00:10:58,003
It's not like you're doing anything different, but somehow the attitude with which you do it is what changes, and that's what turns it into spiritual practice.

80
00:10:58,024 --> 00:11:01,589
So even here now, you see, I keep stressing this business of eating.

81
00:11:01,950 --> 00:11:03,032
So before, we're just eating.

82
00:11:04,815 --> 00:11:10,043
Either our minds are reading the newspaper, or we're just gobbling, or we're overeating.

83
00:11:10,082 --> 00:11:14,190
But suddenly, eating becomes a real spiritual practice in itself.

84
00:11:16,567 --> 00:11:42,269
both by way of developing a certain attitude towards food seeing it as medicine seeing it as nourishment and yet not denying the pleasure this is the point not denying the pleasure there is pleasure that's fine you see but not doing it for that reason not doing it for comfort's sake and the important thing to remember you know is that

85
00:11:42,486 --> 00:11:44,710
The psychology of that runs through everything.

86
00:11:45,191 --> 00:11:46,332
It's not just with eating.

87
00:11:46,974 --> 00:11:49,037
I mean, we're talking about dependent origination.

88
00:11:49,116 --> 00:11:54,826
We're talking about the distinction between the point of vedana and the point of tanha.

89
00:11:54,905 --> 00:12:03,038
Vedana is the point where we experience sensations, feelings in the body, as pleasant or unpleasant.

90
00:12:03,298 --> 00:12:03,860
That's a given.

91
00:12:04,981 --> 00:12:06,924
That's the...

92
00:12:07,326 --> 00:12:09,770
That's what the psycho-physical organism does.

93
00:12:10,692 --> 00:12:13,759
It experiences things and gives us feelings.

94
00:12:16,364 --> 00:12:20,130
But then it's this other business, this tanha, which we've talked about this morning.

95
00:12:23,015 --> 00:12:30,229
So that psychology can be translated to all areas of pleasures and joys in our lives.

96
00:12:30,529 --> 00:12:35,414
See, this is the great thing about the spiritual life, nothing is ever destroyed.

97
00:12:36,075 --> 00:12:40,279
The only thing the Buddha said was destroyed was greed, hatred and delusion.

98
00:12:40,340 --> 00:12:49,448
So everything is handed back, purified of its kinks.

99
00:12:49,969 --> 00:12:55,794
Because of his style of talking about his Dhamma in a more negative sense,

100
00:12:56,432 --> 00:13:20,802
really to undermine concepts about the self and rebirth and all that reincarnation he tended to favor the sort of negative approach so saying that there is see we quote it in the morning there is a not born and not what does that mean see there is a not born what is it you see so of course he won't go that far well he does actually

101
00:13:21,255 --> 00:13:22,298
He does occasionally.

102
00:13:23,019 --> 00:13:24,881
But that's his preferred method.

103
00:13:24,902 --> 00:13:28,048
So of course people would say, well, you're an annihilation, you're a nihilist.

104
00:13:28,708 --> 00:13:31,354
You know, there's not this, not that, so there's nothing.

105
00:13:31,614 --> 00:13:33,197
So therefore you're a nihilist.

106
00:13:33,216 --> 00:13:34,438
So he would constantly say no.

107
00:13:34,458 --> 00:13:38,046
He said no, the only thing that's annihilated is greed, hatred and delusion.

108
00:13:38,066 --> 00:13:44,918
And delusion, by delusion, fundamentally he means this idea, feeling, notion of a self.

109
00:14:07,561 --> 00:14:24,519
So when we're looking at pleasure, you see, when we're looking at pleasure, we're not trying to get rid of pleasure, we're trying to take something out of our relationship with pleasure, trying to reform that relationship.

110
00:14:24,539 --> 00:14:26,402
And it's the same with suffering, see.

111
00:14:26,942 --> 00:14:32,589
It's not as though we can ever get rid of physical suffering, it's just part and parcel of the body's way of being in the world.

112
00:14:34,991 --> 00:14:35,812
Pain.

113
00:14:36,147 --> 00:15:05,900
but we can do something about our relationship to it same with relationships we have difficult relationships you can't do anything about the sort of personality clash but you can find a way of being with it where it's not so painful or take the pain out just accept the person as they are and that process we call the process of liberation that's what we're doing process of liberation

114
00:15:28,644 --> 00:15:35,642
So when we go back and we start with actually, you know, how do we then bring it into daily life?

115
00:15:36,323 --> 00:15:45,085
How does the practice that we do in sitting meditation relate to our daily practice?

116
00:15:45,384 --> 00:15:47,967
then that's really what our task is.

117
00:15:48,268 --> 00:15:59,720
And if we can't relate it, if there's a distinction to be, if there's a hair's breadth of separation between the practice of meditation and the rest of our lives, we've lost it.

118
00:16:01,402 --> 00:16:06,788
Because the Buddha's teaching is centered upon a type of being in the world that we call mindfulness.

119
00:16:07,368 --> 00:16:12,573
So you're here all the time, you're bringing yourself back into the present moment all the time.

120
00:16:13,769 --> 00:16:18,096
And the big trick of that is this business of relaxing.

121
00:16:18,395 --> 00:16:23,222
Can't sort of overstress that, really.

122
00:16:23,243 --> 00:16:36,563
And this relaxing into the present moment, you see, stopping, just allows you to recognize what's there, what's actually driving you at this present time, and allowing it to become very conscious.

123
00:16:37,384 --> 00:16:37,465
See?

124
00:16:39,587 --> 00:16:42,631
and you can let go of things that have been accumulated.

125
00:16:42,692 --> 00:16:48,879
And that way, you not only reserve your energy, you actually take control of your life.

126
00:16:52,684 --> 00:17:04,920
You know, for instance, when sometimes, you know, one is late for work, you find yourself late for work, so there's this anxiety about being late for work, you missed the bus or something.

127
00:17:06,182 --> 00:17:09,929
And you can see that sort of anxiety sort of building up inside you, you see.

128
00:17:11,530 --> 00:17:12,432
And you can't stop it.

129
00:17:12,511 --> 00:17:13,133
This is the point.

130
00:17:13,232 --> 00:17:14,875
You say to yourself, oh, I'm getting anxious.

131
00:17:14,895 --> 00:17:16,057
I won't be anxious, you see.

132
00:17:16,238 --> 00:17:17,640
I'll just get there and start doing the work.

133
00:17:19,982 --> 00:17:22,006
But to do that is to deny your anxiety.

134
00:17:22,207 --> 00:17:24,750
You're up against what's actually happening in your body.

135
00:17:27,535 --> 00:17:32,923
So you have to recognize all this is an old conditioning of getting anxious about being late, you know.

136
00:17:32,942 --> 00:17:34,003
If you're going to be late, you're going to be late.

137
00:17:34,023 --> 00:17:35,987
What's the point of being anxious?

138
00:17:36,085 --> 00:17:40,673
You have to argue yourself out of it, get a different perspective on it.

139
00:17:41,073 --> 00:17:47,002
You can't do anything about the feeling of anxiety because that's coming from a different conditioning, that's happening.

140
00:17:47,844 --> 00:17:49,807
But at least one can stop stoking it.

141
00:17:49,988 --> 00:17:52,592
That's the point, one can stop stoking it.

142
00:17:53,617 --> 00:18:17,719
you do it by turning it into an object there's your meditation right there sitting on the bus or running for the train or driving like mad you see right there you're right there with the feeling of anxiety you know it's there that's enough you're doing your meditation and your attention is on either that if you're sitting in a in a bus or if you're driving of course you're sending to the traffic

143
00:18:27,419 --> 00:18:32,664
So by making that your object, you see, and relaxing, that takes a relaxation.

144
00:18:32,724 --> 00:18:35,208
You have to relax into the present moment.

145
00:18:35,367 --> 00:18:36,650
You have to be with it, you see.

146
00:18:37,131 --> 00:18:55,231
So this practice of relaxing when you begin your meditation, of actually stopping and being in touch with your breath and relaxing into the present moment, here it's easier because you're feeling pleasant neutral feelings, at least it's good to see them as pleasant, neutrally pleasant.

147
00:18:56,713 --> 00:19:09,728
And, you know, you're developing the attitude of just sinking, of just collapsing, you might say, just stopping in the present moment and just accepting what's there.

148
00:19:10,383 --> 00:19:17,413
Normally speaking, we get this anxiety up, we get this rush up, we get to work and we keep going.

149
00:19:18,135 --> 00:19:20,318
It's like it hasn't clicked that we've arrived.

150
00:19:20,900 --> 00:19:29,994
Even if we arrived early actually, we're still rushing, we're still moving at this tremendous pace that we've set ourselves on the perception that we're going to be late.

151
00:19:40,436 --> 00:19:48,884
Then when you're here, now we've got beyond the stage of just watching the breath and now you're open to these negative states within you, right?

152
00:19:49,345 --> 00:19:55,410
So let's say you think a bit depressed, a bit anxious and all that sort of stuff and you're just sitting with the feeling, you see.

153
00:19:56,570 --> 00:20:05,058
Now it's very interesting because in the discourse on how to establish mindfulness, the Buddha always talks about the inside and the outside, the inside and the outside.

154
00:20:05,919 --> 00:20:10,123
And often this outside is commented upon as being aware of other people.

155
00:20:10,356 --> 00:20:34,525
people states so you get to work and somebody else is anxious I mean you're okay you're calm it's worse if you're anxious but they're anxious too see so they start putting this stress on you so our normal people's reaction is to is to respond with with stress themselves I remember this phone call on a

156
00:20:36,142 --> 00:20:59,465
mobile in a train you know and this woman she's her voice is rising and rising and rising you know and then there's suddenly this wonderful statement at the end i'm stressed out i wanted to go over and say look have a cup of tea or something you know relax you know there was a sort of a total desperation in it you know i thought oh god she's in for a little breakdown or something

157
00:21:01,993 --> 00:21:06,559
Now, here we are sitting with this, say, in this sense, these negative emotions.

158
00:21:06,579 --> 00:21:07,101
What are we doing?

159
00:21:07,501 --> 00:21:07,682
See?

160
00:21:10,005 --> 00:21:11,166
We're attending to them.

161
00:21:11,567 --> 00:21:13,869
We're attending to them, like a nurse attends.

162
00:21:13,890 --> 00:21:14,971
We're attending to them.

163
00:21:14,991 --> 00:21:15,853
We know they're there.

164
00:21:16,394 --> 00:21:19,718
We're neither pushing them away, nor are we indulging them.

165
00:21:20,538 --> 00:21:23,763
So, somebody comes to us with stress, that's what you do.

166
00:21:23,983 --> 00:21:25,906
You attend to their stress.

167
00:21:26,948 --> 00:21:29,010
There's no need for you to get stressed because of their stress.

168
00:21:29,030 --> 00:21:29,892
What's the point of that?

169
00:21:31,288 --> 00:21:56,132
so as somebody approaches you with stress or with anger or with their depression you attend to it, your attention is on them and by doing that, by placing your interest into their attention you undermine old habits of reacting to the way you used to react before

170
00:21:56,212 --> 00:21:57,155
Old reactions.

171
00:21:57,616 --> 00:21:58,638
You're not responding.

172
00:21:58,859 --> 00:22:01,307
You're, as it were, undermining that process.

173
00:22:02,871 --> 00:22:04,013
The mind's very quick, isn't it?

174
00:22:04,074 --> 00:22:05,657
It'll flip very quickly, you see.

175
00:22:07,482 --> 00:22:08,586
You know, it's...

176
00:22:10,792 --> 00:22:38,876
things happen just in a second you know you might be calm for a moment with somebody who's angry next minute you've lost it you know you've got yourself angry you see so these things so you've got to keep that real sharp awareness and in order to do that it has to be backed with the right attitude you see and if we haven't really grasped the right attitude then it's very difficult to to stop that reaction even though we might be good-willed

177
00:22:40,747 --> 00:22:51,181
