00:23:54,453 --> 00:23:59,521
And that's what happens, isn't it, when you get caught up in somebody else's emotional state.

192
00:24:03,046 --> 00:24:15,739
So in our relationships, both in our personal, more intimate relationships and in work situations,

193
00:24:16,106 --> 00:24:28,325
It's just maintaining that attitude of knowing that if one reacts in a negative way to somebody else's negativity, then you both jump off the bridge.

194
00:24:28,684 --> 00:24:30,326
It's as simple as that.

195
00:24:30,347 --> 00:24:39,760
So when that's actually been, when that's saturated, when that's really saturated your being, you see, then you've established a different attitude.

196
00:24:40,281 --> 00:24:43,886
That doesn't mean to say that the old conditionings aren't going to be there.

197
00:24:43,866 --> 00:24:48,913
So if somebody comes to you in anger, you can feel, you can feel the whole condition, you want a bite, you see.

198
00:24:49,595 --> 00:24:58,448
But because you've established this attitude, you very quickly know that all the person wants is for you to listen to them, isn't it?

199
00:24:58,909 --> 00:25:03,474
When you're angry, isn't it, all you want to do is for them to listen to what you're saying.

200
00:25:03,494 --> 00:25:09,604
Not only listen in the sense of what you're saying, but what you're feeling, you know, like I am angry with you, you know.

201
00:25:11,440 --> 00:25:15,866
And it's been able just to stay with that in that sort of attending way, you see.

202
00:25:16,346 --> 00:25:20,393
Not in this sort of, I think the word is passive-aggressive, isn't it?

203
00:25:21,054 --> 00:25:22,195
Or aggressive passivity.

204
00:25:22,236 --> 00:25:26,923
It's like you're standing there, you know, and you're not touching me.

205
00:25:27,202 --> 00:25:28,424
Well, I mean, that's really aggressive.

206
00:25:29,165 --> 00:25:31,068
That's going to make them really want to bite.

207
00:25:32,045 --> 00:25:45,364
But if you manifest the fact that you feel their anger, and there's that empathy with their anger and whatnot, then there's not that aggressive response.

208
00:25:46,506 --> 00:25:46,665
See?

209
00:25:53,855 --> 00:25:56,339
You've always got that magic word, sorry, you see?

210
00:25:56,500 --> 00:25:58,643
That drains people's anger, you know?

211
00:25:59,180 --> 00:26:02,424
And then after you've done that, of course, you prove it was their fault anyway.

212
00:26:05,429 --> 00:26:06,691
You win anyway.

213
00:26:06,931 --> 00:26:11,196
Be careful of that.

214
00:26:11,217 --> 00:26:12,880
A one-up, you know, gotcha.

215
00:26:16,744 --> 00:26:24,336
And it's... Now, can you see the link between sitting with your own mental states and sitting with somebody else's?

216
00:26:24,355 --> 00:26:26,038
The inside and the outside.

217
00:26:26,199 --> 00:26:28,883
You're taking the practice directly into your daily life.

218
00:26:29,452 --> 00:26:57,250
when it comes to insight so all this really is about creating peaceful states around us how is it that we have this special practice called vipassana which is about seeing these three characteristics how does that work how does that translate into your daily life because I mean it's only with those sorts of insights that there are radical changes these are root changes

219
00:26:57,230 --> 00:27:22,883
we can change our personalities we can change our attitudes we can do a lot to change the surface psychology you can even change your body you can do a bit of exercise and stuff like that but it's not getting to the root of it the root problems are to do with these wrong ways of seeing things so where we see permanence there is impermanence

220
00:27:22,863 --> 00:27:32,438
Now you might say, well, I can see impermanence everywhere, but the fact is, when we're struck by crises, then of course we find it a big shock.

221
00:27:33,058 --> 00:27:43,233
It's the level of shock, it's the level of fear which shows us our relationship to a situation which we thought was steady, permanent, unchangeable.

222
00:27:45,272 --> 00:27:48,001
And then there's that business of the wanting and not wanting.

223
00:27:48,363 --> 00:27:53,420
So yeah, that's a bit more obvious, taking that into daily life, and we'll come back to that.

224
00:27:53,820 --> 00:27:57,814
And then there's this other business of anatta, not self, you see.

225
00:27:59,261 --> 00:28:11,224
When you're sitting like this, of course, it's a privileged position because you have found this objective observer place, this observation post, as Jnana Ponica calls it.

226
00:28:11,265 --> 00:28:15,594
He's a pretty famous writer in Theravada, a German.

227
00:28:15,894 --> 00:28:17,237
He's died now.

228
00:28:17,217 --> 00:28:20,383
an observation post, you found this observation post within yourself.

229
00:28:20,462 --> 00:28:26,334
So this is a fairly privileged position you might say, because you're not moving, you're not doing anything, so now you can watch.

230
00:28:26,634 --> 00:28:30,141
You can watch the psychophysical organism in action.

231
00:28:30,622 --> 00:28:34,809
You can see the body feels, the heart emotes, and the mind thinks.

232
00:28:35,531 --> 00:28:36,192
What else is there?

233
00:28:37,075 --> 00:28:37,655
What else is there?

234
00:28:37,675 --> 00:28:38,938
That's it.

235
00:28:39,289 --> 00:29:05,230
and you can see that things are changing you can see how you're relating to what's inside you and that's something coming from this wrong idea of indulgence and resistance and you can see this business of not me not mine as you become very clear in your seeing that these are objects

236
00:29:05,902 --> 00:29:07,625
So what's an object can't be the subject.

237
00:29:07,644 --> 00:29:08,365
It's as simple as that.

238
00:29:09,126 --> 00:29:12,553
Even the feeling of self-awareness, as we said, is an object.

239
00:29:13,074 --> 00:29:15,156
You're aware of a self, so you can't be that either.

240
00:29:16,439 --> 00:29:22,189
But it's actually looking at that and constantly re-experiencing that makes these things very obvious to you.

241
00:29:23,941 --> 00:29:29,928
So now how can you have, you know, a spiritual insight in daily life?

242
00:29:29,948 --> 00:29:36,556
You know, when you're sort of washing the pots or when you're talking to somebody or when you're doing a job and all that, you see.

243
00:29:37,958 --> 00:29:52,615
Well, the understanding is that this intelligence that is the knowing, this intuitive intelligence, which is prior, prior to the mind with its thoughts, yeah, it's prior to emotions, right,

244
00:29:53,101 --> 00:29:57,007
Most people think of intuitive intelligence as a feeling.

245
00:29:57,528 --> 00:30:07,223
Sure, it manifests, it sort of communicates its understanding through feeling, but it's not feeling, it's not emotion, and it's not the body either.

246
00:30:08,506 --> 00:30:12,392
And that's what we're discovering every time we access this observation post.

247
00:30:14,768 --> 00:30:40,641
now that intelligence is being primed every time you sit to begin to see life from one of these three perspectives every time you sit, every time you make the conscious effort to see these three characteristics it is being informed, it's informing itself and that manifests in your daily life in various ways

248
00:30:41,144 --> 00:30:57,185
So when this tsunami struck Sri Lanka, there were some very well-meaning counselors went there to help people overcome their trauma.

