To me, it's a nightmare.

279
00:34:04,268 --> 00:34:16,625
So it's a case of, you know, once we grasp the impermanence, you see, it takes away the reverberation of disaster.

280
00:34:17,985 --> 00:34:22,351
It takes away the reverberation of loss, of grief, and that sort of stuff.

281
00:34:22,371 --> 00:34:25,896
There is just the grief, there is just the loss, you know.

282
00:34:26,317 --> 00:34:29,702
There's not behind it some feeling of injustice, you know.

283
00:34:31,032 --> 00:34:34,936
Human beings are always clever at making themselves the center of the universe.

284
00:34:34,996 --> 00:34:39,503
It was such a clout to our ego when we realized that the earth actually went round the sun.

285
00:34:40,164 --> 00:34:45,630
And it was even worse when we were told that we were just animals.

286
00:34:47,773 --> 00:34:49,936
We just rose up from the animals.

287
00:34:49,956 --> 00:34:51,838
We were just fitter, that's all.

288
00:34:52,739 --> 00:34:56,744
That was a hit, wasn't it, to the old ego.

289
00:34:58,887 --> 00:35:00,329
So this...

290
00:35:00,530 --> 00:35:10,905
This sense of, what we do as humans, we project our sense of justice onto the universe.

291
00:35:10,925 --> 00:35:14,090
There's no justice in the universe, there's only laws, yeah?

292
00:35:14,731 --> 00:35:20,298
You know, tsunamis happen because earthquakes happen under the sea or something, or a tectonic plate shift.

293
00:35:20,318 --> 00:35:26,588
Nothing to do with justice, nothing to do with morality, nothing to do with the way the earth is, it's that sort of law, you know?

294
00:35:28,492 --> 00:35:35,777
So when people say, oh, well, you know, it's a shame he died young and all that, you know, like it's a law.

295
00:35:35,817 --> 00:35:40,914
The body runs along different laws from human justice, and that's the way it is.

296
00:35:44,353 --> 00:35:51,246
So just getting the idea of impermanence, saturating the way we look at things, everything's impermanent, you see.

297
00:35:51,768 --> 00:35:54,672
Even to get up in the morning and say to yourself, everything's impermanent.

298
00:35:54,693 --> 00:35:55,775
I don't know what's going to happen today.

299
00:35:56,356 --> 00:35:57,378
I think I know what's going to happen.

300
00:35:57,637 --> 00:35:58,599
I've got it all planned.

301
00:36:00,418 --> 00:36:28,688
I actually don't know what's going to happen see so that puts us into this into this mind you see framework you see and the Buddha's great statement about impermanence is that you know when we actually grasp impermanence in its real fullness we realize there's nothing in the world worth holding on to nothing in the world worth holding on to not even ourselves this is the point

302
00:36:30,355 --> 00:36:36,003
Now that, at first, you know, at first it might strike as sort of, you know, a bit frightening and whatnot.

303
00:36:36,023 --> 00:36:37,626
But it's tremendously relaxing, isn't it?

304
00:36:37,847 --> 00:36:39,148
We don't have to hold on to anything anymore.

305
00:36:39,429 --> 00:36:39,809
Yippee!

306
00:36:40,289 --> 00:36:46,320
So it's like when somebody, you know, thieves something from you, you see.

307
00:36:47,460 --> 00:36:51,067
You know, we have this idea that I possess something, see.

308
00:36:51,086 --> 00:36:54,371
So I possess my...

309
00:36:54,773 --> 00:36:55,373
Mobile.

310
00:36:55,715 --> 00:36:57,358
It's my mobile.

311
00:36:57,398 --> 00:36:58,981
I can prove it in law.

312
00:37:00,324 --> 00:37:01,284
This belongs to me.

313
00:37:01,365 --> 00:37:02,146
I'm attached to it.

314
00:37:03,088 --> 00:37:05,994
And then somebody steals it, and I'm still going around saying it's my mobile.

315
00:37:08,418 --> 00:37:09,661
It's the thief's.

316
00:37:10,483 --> 00:37:13,708
The thief owns the mobile.

317
00:37:13,728 --> 00:37:16,233
And I'm suffering like mad because they've got my mobile.

318
00:37:17,054 --> 00:37:17,996
I didn't tell them, you know.

319
00:37:21,199 --> 00:37:25,753
And suddenly when you realize, actually, you can't own anything.

320
00:37:25,893 --> 00:37:27,358
What you can do is use it.

321
00:37:27,719 --> 00:37:28,460
Ah, what a relief.

322
00:37:29,003 --> 00:37:29,784
See?

323
00:37:29,804 --> 00:37:33,135
And then you think, well, you know, the thief might need it more than me.

324
00:37:33,175 --> 00:37:34,297
And you're happy to give it away.

325
00:37:34,699 --> 00:37:35,360
Just like that.

326
00:37:38,632 --> 00:37:42,898
So that impermanence, you see, it seeps into an attitude.

327
00:37:43,478 --> 00:37:46,623
And that's important to understand that.

328
00:37:46,643 --> 00:37:52,610
The Eightfold Path begins with right understanding, and the second one is right attitude.

329
00:37:53,813 --> 00:37:57,757
And if it doesn't drop into an attitude, it just remains at this nice intellectual level.

330
00:37:57,958 --> 00:37:59,800
Oh yeah, everything arises and passes away.

331
00:37:59,820 --> 00:38:00,681
You know, what?

332
00:38:03,085 --> 00:38:06,630
There's no catastrophe when something does arise and pass away, you know.

333
00:38:06,847 --> 00:38:10,530
So it has to sink into, and that's a heart state.

334
00:38:11,570 --> 00:38:14,554
When I say heart state here, I'm not talking really about an emotion.

335
00:38:14,793 --> 00:38:16,356
So an attitude isn't an emotion.

336
00:38:17,195 --> 00:38:18,597
You have to be clear about that.

337
00:38:19,038 --> 00:38:23,081
An attitude is a way of relating as an attitude.

338
00:38:23,862 --> 00:38:25,804
An understanding, everything's impermanent.

339
00:38:26,425 --> 00:38:34,271
What does that mean in terms of my relationship to objects, my relationship to people, my relationship to myself, my own body?

340
00:38:34,251 --> 00:38:42,237
see how does that relate and that's your attitude and then of course it manifests in the way we behave in the way we do actually relate moment to moment

341
00:38:48,324 --> 00:38:52,791
Now the next one, you see, which seeps into our daily life is this business of dukkha.

342
00:38:52,891 --> 00:38:55,695
So dukkha, remember, is one of these big words in Buddhism.

343
00:38:55,715 --> 00:39:03,324
It sort of covers everything that makes us unhappy in the widest sense of that meaning.

344
00:39:03,425 --> 00:39:14,298
You know, from the trivialist things, something like that, the most trivial, that's better, from the most trivial thing to, you know, catastrophes.

345
00:39:14,278 --> 00:39:22,655
The whole gamut of human misery is contained in this word dukkha, which actually means a hard place.

346
00:39:22,936 --> 00:39:23,476
That's what it means.

347
00:39:23,496 --> 00:39:24,960
This is a hard place.

348
00:39:26,481 --> 00:39:31,172
And when the Buddha says, you know, go into this, where is the suffering?

349
00:39:31,192 --> 00:39:36,641
Then it's to do with this psychology of wanting and not wanting, wanting and not wanting.

350
00:39:38,612 --> 00:39:51,568
Now, just a very sort of change of attitude, you know, just a change of words, like, you know, not getting what you want, but wanting what you get.

351
00:39:52,409 --> 00:39:59,717
So even that, wanting what you get, there's a sort of flip, you know, and you think, oh, and suddenly you're contented.

352
00:40:00,318 --> 00:40:06,644
You know, to be actually, to develop the attitude of contentment with what I've got, you know.

353
00:40:06,945 --> 00:40:19,481
And of course it's difficult in a society which is driven by consumerism, because consumerism depends on your constant discontent.

354
00:40:20,362 --> 00:40:22,503
As soon as you're contented, that's it.

355
00:40:22,583 --> 00:40:25,327
Consumerism collapses the whole industrial base.

356
00:40:26,668 --> 00:40:28,670
I don't want a car, I'm content, I'll walk.

357
00:40:31,614 --> 00:40:32,615
You can't do that.

358
00:40:33,186 --> 00:40:34,791
You've got to be discontent.

359
00:40:34,811 --> 00:40:42,172
So this whole feeling of constantly being discontent, the whole of the advert is to make you feel discontent.

360
00:40:43,675 --> 00:40:46,402
That's why you want that, you know, whatever it is, you know.

361
00:40:47,902 --> 00:40:58,840
But constantly saying to ourselves, constantly beginning from the platform of, this is okay, this is the way it is, it's fine, it's not a problem, it's good, it's the way it is, content, you see.

362
00:40:59,702 --> 00:41:02,806
And what you do is you begin to separate need from want.

363
00:41:03,387 --> 00:41:06,753
Sometimes you need, you need a new pair of shoes and that's the end of it.

364
00:41:07,121 --> 00:41:08,324
So you go and get a pair of shoes.

365
00:41:08,664 --> 00:41:10,887
And then there's that dividing line.

366
00:41:10,927 --> 00:41:13,251
So you now know this is need, this is want.

367
00:41:13,751 --> 00:41:16,795
Wants come up sometimes for various reasons.

368
00:41:16,936 --> 00:41:22,123
Say to lift your spirit, you might buy yourself something rather pleasant or ask somebody else to do it.

369
00:41:25,027 --> 00:41:32,860
But at least there's not this churning of the heart that could go out and constantly exercise this retail therapy.

370
00:41:33,295 --> 00:41:38,143
Seeking comfort in shops, for heaven's sake.

371
00:41:38,163 --> 00:41:38,804
Ridiculous.

372
00:41:41,849 --> 00:41:44,875
I don't feel comfortable unless I'm in Marks and Spencer's.

373
00:41:45,976 --> 00:41:47,699
Ridiculous, isn't it?

374
00:41:48,320 --> 00:41:49,402
Where do I go when I'm sad?

375
00:41:49,682 --> 00:41:50,503
Marks and Spencer's.

376
00:41:51,887 --> 00:41:56,755
When I feel depressed, I go to Marks and Spencer's.

377
00:41:57,072 --> 00:42:01,237
Like it's been a disaster, Woolworths has gone.

378
00:42:01,257 --> 00:42:05,824
Like it's a catastrophe, Woolworths has gone.

379
00:42:06,666 --> 00:42:09,809
Oh my God.

380
00:42:10,550 --> 00:42:13,675
Weird sort of ways of relating to the world.

381
00:42:14,376 --> 00:42:20,244
So you can see that even now, we're watching the suffering of wanting, not wanting.

382
00:42:21,844 --> 00:42:47,733
you know a desire comes up we want to think about this we want to plan our holiday you know and we're constantly pulling ourselves off and feeling that that strong desire that that willfulness in us you see when it's something unpleasant you see that's even more that's sort of more difficult but to be able to be uh to be able to be easy with unpleasantness see now it's cold the difference between a room temperature and outside is vicious

383
00:42:48,322 --> 00:42:52,708
And, you know, our attitude is to sort of resist the cold.

384
00:42:52,728 --> 00:43:00,481
We sort of, you know, rush from the bungalow to here to get out of the cold instead of sort of greeting it.

385
00:43:00,501 --> 00:43:01,422
Ah, cold, great.

386
00:43:01,722 --> 00:43:06,990
You know, the freshness of it, you know.

387
00:43:07,010 --> 00:43:08,793
I'm not suggesting you catch a cold, you understand.

388
00:43:11,795 --> 00:43:14,579
And to take that attitude into daily life.

389
00:43:15,021 --> 00:43:15,461
You can do it.

390
00:43:15,641 --> 00:43:16,063
You can do it.

391
00:43:16,483 --> 00:43:20,271
And again, it's sort of reminding ourselves, this constant self-reminder.

392
00:43:20,291 --> 00:43:25,460
So as soon as we see ourselves passing a shop and wanting that, yeah, hold on.

393
00:43:25,601 --> 00:43:30,411
Just pull it back, you know, pull back that sort of energy, you see.

394
00:43:30,391 --> 00:43:41,731
And of course it can be, and all that energy, by the way, that we're using in getting what we want, it's not being wasted, you can displace it, you can take your interest elsewhere.

395
00:43:41,791 --> 00:43:48,501
You know, in the old days they used to talk about sublimation, sort of a religious idea of sublimating your desires, you know.

396
00:43:49,023 --> 00:43:51,166
You don't hear that word often these days, you know.

397
00:43:51,552 --> 00:44:05,672
And that's because, really, I suppose, through the agencies of people like Freud, people think that there are certain instincts and desires that are blocked or locked into certain things, like our sexual appetite.

398
00:44:05,693 --> 00:44:07,755
They're just stuck there and you can't get rid of them.

399
00:44:08,577 --> 00:44:16,108
But in spiritual terms, sublimation means that you guide that energy and put it somewhere else.

400
00:44:16,088 --> 00:44:16,869
It's all it is.

401
00:44:17,110 --> 00:44:23,639
The mind and body, as we know from our great quantum physics, is that it's just energy.

402
00:44:24,342 --> 00:44:35,940
So if you decide to displace the energy, you see, away from, say, eroticism, and you put it into art, then that's your sublimation, you know.

403
00:44:36,922 --> 00:44:38,485
That's what you mean by sublimating.

404
00:44:40,050 --> 00:44:51,728
And that transference, that transformation of energy, away from desires which you see are unwholesome, to desires which you see are wholesome, is part and parcel of that process.

405
00:44:52,070 --> 00:45:06,092
I'm not suggesting that erotic desires are per se unwholesome, they obviously have their place in time, but if you find them sort of cringing on the mind, sort of obsessive,

406
00:45:06,847 --> 00:45:10,815
It's a case of slowly displacing them, putting our interests elsewhere.

407
00:45:14,463 --> 00:45:15,846
So it's the same with shopping, you see.

408
00:45:17,389 --> 00:45:22,039
People put a lot of interest in shopping, in fashion and all that sort of stuff.

409
00:45:22,389 --> 00:45:28,876
All they have to do is just to draw their interest elsewhere, just to re-educate themselves.

410
00:45:28,896 --> 00:45:29,456
That's all it is.

411
00:45:29,476 --> 00:45:31,498
It's just a process of re-education.

412
00:45:31,998 --> 00:45:33,920
But they won't do it unless they see the suffering.

413
00:45:34,081 --> 00:45:34,641
That's the point.

414
00:45:35,222 --> 00:45:42,349
And the problem with pleasure, the problem with joy, indulgent joy, is that while you're in it, it's great.

415
00:45:42,710 --> 00:45:43,389
That's the problem.

416
00:45:43,871 --> 00:45:48,195
And you're prepared often to suffer the consequences so you can have this bit of joy.

417
00:45:53,490 --> 00:45:55,333
It's only when you get the comeback, you know.

418
00:45:55,893 --> 00:46:02,722
I was just thinking there of a friend who, a friend's father, you see, always smoked, always smoked, you see.

419
00:46:03,001 --> 00:46:06,206
Then he had a heart attack, and he suddenly stopped, just like that.

420
00:46:07,387 --> 00:46:08,387
He got the comeback.

421
00:46:08,809 --> 00:46:12,753
It's unfortunate that it was so strong a comeback, but it just shows, you know.

422
00:46:13,213 --> 00:46:20,021
Now, the comeback of all indulgence is, you know, the craving.

423
00:46:21,284 --> 00:46:24,206
The possibility of grief, if you lose what it is, you treasure.

424
00:46:25,389 --> 00:46:31,235
The anxiety, once you've got something, the anxiety of losing it, that's why we've got a massive insurance industry.

425
00:46:33,677 --> 00:46:36,922
And of course the frustration, not getting it when you want.

426
00:46:36,942 --> 00:46:37,583
Getting what you want.

427
00:46:38,344 --> 00:46:48,996
So by taking this inner understanding of wanting, not wanting, into daily life, you see, it moves you towards contentment.

428
00:46:49,903 --> 00:46:52,449
That's the joy, that's the subtle joy.

429
00:46:52,690 --> 00:47:01,449
And that's another reason why to develop this calmness on the breath and to begin to see it is actually a very delicious place to be.

430
00:47:01,581 --> 00:47:08,311
Often we find it, but we do it in contrast to agitation, in contrast to stress.

431
00:47:08,831 --> 00:47:16,143
We'll go home and just flop in the chair, and just for a moment there's no radio, there's no nothing, we just sort of sink into the quietness of the moment.

432
00:47:16,844 --> 00:47:26,356
We might walk into a park, or come out into the country, or sit in the garden, and just for a moment we'll actually sink into that space, to that little bit of peace, you see.

433
00:47:26,708 --> 00:47:30,552
but we'll do it as a sort of antidote to another thing.

434
00:47:30,813 --> 00:47:42,650
Whereas what we want to do is to develop it as a prime condition, something that we can return to at any time, and as it were, remains a substrate beneath our psychology.

435
00:47:43,251 --> 00:47:49,099
There's always this deep sense of calmness within us, no matter what we're doing on the surface.

436
00:47:50,342 --> 00:47:51,884
And again, it's just training.

437
00:47:51,903 --> 00:47:53,525
It's just training ourselves to do that.

438
00:47:54,737 --> 00:47:59,166
So the breath there is watching the breath, feeling the breath.

439
00:47:59,186 --> 00:48:04,539
Seeing it as a place where we can develop this calmness and peace is directly related into daily life.

440
00:48:05,581 --> 00:48:07,143
Because you can always come back to your breath.

441
00:48:08,963 --> 00:48:22,009
You know, when I say stop every so often, you know, just come to an end of what you're doing, you see, and catch what it is you've accumulated, some anxiety, some stress, whatever, and allow it to pass, there's always the breath, you see.

442
00:48:22,028 --> 00:48:27,159
And the breath will be a place that you'll go to, just like your garden or the park.

443
00:48:27,179 --> 00:48:30,887
It's a place where you just find that inner peace for a moment.

444
00:48:36,114 --> 00:48:51,463
Now the sense of not-self is one of the key factors and it's in his second talk, the second talk he gives to his five disciples, at the end of which they're all fully liberated by the way.

445
00:48:51,483 --> 00:49:00,199
He says clearly, he says, that which arises and passes away cannot be under your control.

446
00:49:00,280 --> 00:49:14,067
Now, every time you get into the self, one of the ways that the self manifests is the desire to control power.

447
00:49:15,650 --> 00:49:22,422
Every time you see yourself wanting to control a situation, control a person, you'll know it's coming from the self.

448
00:49:23,315 --> 00:49:30,003
It's not the same as being in charge or being an authority in which you are given the power to make decisions.

449
00:49:30,682 --> 00:49:38,652
I mean, that's an occasion where you take on responsibility and you try to make the wisest decisions you can.

450
00:49:39,532 --> 00:49:52,527
But in terms of this other business, where things are not going your way and you're getting angry, where you're getting angry with your spouse, your partner, because they're not doing what you want them to do, or your kids...

451
00:49:53,655 --> 00:49:56,108
and you're getting frustrated and anxious and all that.

452
00:49:56,793 --> 00:50:00,291
And that's all to do with this sense of wanting to control, you see.

453
00:50:05,248 --> 00:50:25,434
So again, it's this business of taking that into daily life and just recognizing that our control over things is pretty limited and that things happen outside of our control and that there's, in the old phrase, you've got to go with the flow, you've got to be in harmony with what's happening.

454
00:50:25,414 --> 00:50:31,023
That harmony is not always pleasant, but you're actually moving with it.

455
00:50:31,202 --> 00:50:35,108
You're not trying to control something which is actually outside your control.

456
00:50:36,010 --> 00:50:49,329
And I think this comes most obvious with, you know, when we get involved in politics, politics in the wider sense of the meaning, people's issues like, you know, the business going on with climate change and all.

457
00:50:49,309 --> 00:51:00,568
the economy and all that sort of stuff which are not to be confused with sort of small party politics and

458
00:51:01,713 --> 00:51:06,500
One can see what has to be done, everyone can see what has to be done, but there's not the political will.

459
00:51:07,300 --> 00:51:07,981
You can see, you see.

460
00:51:08,181 --> 00:51:11,686
So there arises in people a certain frustration, you see.

461
00:51:12,228 --> 00:51:20,840
And that's really not accepting these two rings that are around us, the first one being one of power, what you can do to help the situation.

462
00:51:21,701 --> 00:51:25,847
And if you step beyond that, you're into frustration, you're into despair.

463
00:51:26,047 --> 00:51:53,050
and that takes an act of humility humility it doesn't mean you know humble humble it just means seeing yourself as you really are that's what humility originally meant and the other ring is influence whereby you can get other people to do what you think is right beyond that there's nothing you do nothing you can do in any physical sense but we do have another outlet which allows us to feel at least that we are

464
00:51:54,547 --> 00:52:00,201
shall we say, in communion, you know, and that is, of course, to offer metta.

465
00:52:00,360 --> 00:52:11,967
I mean, that's the joy of metta, that you can do nothing, but at least you can send out, you know, thoughts of intentions, goodwill intentions towards a situation.

466
00:52:15,202 --> 00:52:27,829
even if we don't believe that they actually affect people, at least it's a way in which we might feel within ourselves that we're doing what we can, full stop, develop a goodwill.

467
00:52:30,577 --> 00:52:37,688
Now, such is the quality of this intuitive intelligence, you see, is that it can have insights at any time.

468
00:52:38,248 --> 00:52:45,179
And it's well known in the Mahasi tradition that insights don't normally come when you're sitting.

469
00:52:45,840 --> 00:52:48,264
It's when you get up and do something that the insights come.

470
00:52:49,307 --> 00:52:56,039
And the reason is that often when we're sitting, we're very subtly trying to achieve something, trying to see something.

471
00:52:56,059 --> 00:53:00,447
And then when we get up from the posture, we sort of say, all right, nothing happened there, forget it, you know, and off we go.

472
00:53:02,391 --> 00:53:07,940
But we retain that mindfulness and lo and behold, there are these sudden insights that come.

473
00:53:08,782 --> 00:53:16,179
Because this intelligence has been released from this craving, been released from the self just for that moment.

474
00:53:16,199 --> 00:53:22,976
So it's not as though insights can't come at any time of the day, any time you're awake, once this mindfulness is established.

475
00:53:25,505 --> 00:53:33,639
In fact, the Mahāsī's teacher, that's the Mahāsī, in case you didn't know, when he was about 50, I suppose.

476
00:53:34,400 --> 00:53:46,862
The Mahāsī's teacher is said to have intuited in anicca, the impermanence, as a direct experience of momentary arising and passing away as a dog passed by.

477
00:53:47,503 --> 00:53:49,706
There wasn't a dog, there was just a dogging.

478
00:53:50,175 --> 00:53:53,762
The dog arose and passed away momentarily.

479
00:53:53,782 --> 00:53:55,204
Because that's the teaching of anicca.

480
00:53:55,384 --> 00:54:03,556
It isn't something which is changing in the sense that you might take a piece of clay and you make a cup and then you screw it up and you make a saucer.

481
00:54:03,617 --> 00:54:04,458
So it's the same clay.

482
00:54:05,840 --> 00:54:07,242
And the Buddha's teaching is quite radical.

483
00:54:07,503 --> 00:54:10,208
It actually collapses into potential or nothing.

484
00:54:10,228 --> 00:54:11,409
I can't say nothing.

485
00:54:11,469 --> 00:54:12,891
It collapses into a potential.

486
00:54:12,952 --> 00:54:13,893
It's not there.

487
00:54:14,333 --> 00:54:16,498
And out of there, it arises again.

488
00:54:17,059 --> 00:54:17,179
Right?

489
00:54:19,268 --> 00:54:48,820
that's what's happening the universe is stroboscopic it's not continuous in the Buddhist teaching so for him that was a deep enough insight for what we call one of the paths and fruits stream entrance or whatever level he was at so that's I hope I've sort of made fairly clear the intimate connection between your meditation and daily life yes

490
00:54:50,487 --> 00:54:52,992
If I happen you, you can leave little notes of complaint.

491
00:54:58,603 --> 00:54:59,043
Kindly.

492
00:55:00,085 --> 00:55:03,652
Notes of complaint.

493
00:55:14,094 --> 00:55:18,623
And remember that the root thing is this constant establishment of mindfulness.

494
00:55:18,882 --> 00:55:26,516
And just as a last word, in the discourse on loving-kindness, can you pass me your book there, please?

495
00:55:27,878 --> 00:55:29,501
Which we chant in the morning, you see.

496
00:55:29,621 --> 00:55:32,766
The Buddha's urging us to develop this loving-kindness.

497
00:55:34,329 --> 00:55:38,835
And at the end, you see, where is he sitting now?

498
00:55:38,916 --> 00:55:39,376
Just a minute.

499
00:55:43,440 --> 00:55:48,648
So he says, whether you are standing, walking, sitting, or lying down.

500
00:55:48,989 --> 00:55:51,893
So those are the same instructions for mindfulness.

501
00:55:52,635 --> 00:55:53,476
Sitting, walking, right?

502
00:55:53,496 --> 00:55:55,519
In other words, in any posture, doing anything.

503
00:55:56,561 --> 00:56:02,030
So long as you're awake, so long as you are mindful, you should develop this mindfulness.

504
00:56:02,110 --> 00:56:07,557
And here, he's talking about a mindfulness saturated with loving-kindness.

505
00:56:07,606 --> 00:56:09,349
saturated with goodwill.

506
00:56:09,409 --> 00:56:11,211
That's a bit better.

507
00:56:11,413 --> 00:56:11,833
Goodwill.

508
00:56:11,853 --> 00:56:13,376
Because it's not meant to be an emotional thing.

509
00:56:14,478 --> 00:56:16,362
This, they say, is the noblest way to live.

510
00:56:16,681 --> 00:56:26,840
And if you do not fall into bad ways, but live well and develop insight, and are no longer attached to all the desires of the senses, then truly you will never need to be reborn to this world again.

511
00:56:27,742 --> 00:56:28,463
So there you have it.

512
00:56:29,684 --> 00:56:31,909
Mindfulness saturated with goodwill.

513
00:56:32,902 --> 00:56:39,371
And in the morning when I, after chanting, I say, you know, make your resolution for the day, you see.

514
00:56:39,411 --> 00:56:44,617
That's an important moment, you see, because that's going to set the underground tone of the day.

515
00:56:45,278 --> 00:56:55,112
So find a little phrase for yourself, you know, to live consciously with goodwill or something like that which strikes you as the way you want to be.

516
00:56:55,092 --> 00:57:02,342
It's also good to also create something where, you know, something that you're not going to do.

517
00:57:02,963 --> 00:57:04,905
You're not going to go down that road today.

518
00:57:05,447 --> 00:57:06,608
Keep it in today, you see.

519
00:57:06,668 --> 00:57:07,530
Don't go beyond today.

520
00:57:07,550 --> 00:57:09,713
It gets depressing.

521
00:57:09,733 --> 00:57:11,976
Because I think I'm going to be like this for the rest of my life.

522
00:57:13,699 --> 00:57:16,782
But if you do it day by day, it's manageable, isn't it?

523
00:57:16,963 --> 00:57:17,463
Just today.

524
00:57:17,724 --> 00:57:19,186
Today I'll be good, see.

525
00:57:19,206 --> 00:57:20,809
Tomorrow I'll play hell.

526
00:57:20,829 --> 00:57:21,690
But today...

527
00:57:22,918 --> 00:57:23,862
We'll keep doing that.

528
00:57:24,744 --> 00:57:27,713
We should arrive, you see.

529
00:57:27,733 --> 00:57:30,300
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

530
00:57:31,021 --> 00:57:38,041
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

